statement:
Find the coefficients \emph{c\textsubscript{n}} in the Fourier series
$f(x) = \sum_{n = -\infty}^\infty c_n e^{2\pi inx}$ if

\begin{align*}f(x) = \begin{cases}
1, & 0 \leq x < 1/2 \\
0, & 1/2 \leq x \leq 1
\end{cases}\end{align*}

sols:
Since $e^{i2\pi nx}$ is an orthonormal basis for any function in the
Hilbert Space we can use the inner product to find the coefficients:

\begin{align*}\left \langle e^{i2\pi mx},f(x) \right \rangle =\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}c_n \left \langle e^{i2\pi mx},e^{i2\pi nx} \right \rangle=c_mL\end{align*}

Therefore we get:

\begin{align*}c_n=\frac{1}{L}\int_{a}^{b}e^{-2\pi inx/L}f(x)dx\end{align*}

Computing this for the given function

\begin{align*}
c_0 &= \frac{1}{1}[\int_{0}^{1/2}e^{-i2\pi (0)x}dx+\int_{1/2}^{1}e^{-i2\pi (0)x}(0)dx] = \frac{1}{2} \\
c_n &= \frac{1}{1}[\int_{0}^{1/2}e^{-i2\pi nx}dx+\int_{1/2}^{1}e^{-i2\pi nx}(0)dx] \\
&=\frac{-1}{i2\pi n}e^{-i2\pi nx} \Big|_0^{1/2} =\frac{-1}{i2\pi n}[e^{-i\pi n}-e^0] \\
&=\frac{i}{2\pi n}[(-1)^n-1]\end{align*}

$c_n=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{2} & \text{if } n=0 \\ 
0 & \text{if } n \text{ is even, } n \not= 0\\ 
\frac{-i}{\pi n} & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}
\end{cases}$
